\begin_layout Abstract
Persistent neural activity in the oculomotor system is used to generate
 stable gaze and high-acuity vision.
 This neural drive is provided by an integrator circuit that temporally
 integrates eye velocity signals to generate eye position commands.
 To help determine the circuit organization of the oculomotor neural integrator,
 we coupled two-photon microscopy with serial electron microscopy of the
 larval zebrafish hindbrain to link integrator neuron function and ultrastructur
e.
 Integrator neuron activity was imaged using calcium sensors while the animal
 made spontaneous saccades and gaze fixations.
 After tissue processing, the same neurons were then identified and reconstructe
d at the ultrastructure level.
 Our reconstructions revealed integrator cells with varied dendritic morphologie
s, axonal projections and synaptic distributions.
 Cells at rostral and medial locations had ipsilaterally projecting axons,
 while cells that were caudal had contralaterally projecting axons.
 We found synaptic contacts from ipsilaterally-projecting neurons onto integrato
r neurons from either projection class.
 The axons of these cells exhibited significant clustering.
 Furthermore, the neurotransmitter identity of integrator neurons can be
 inferred by somatic locations of cells that are known to follow a stereotypic
 expression pattern in larval zebrafish.
 Based on this, we speculate that cells with ipsilaterally projecting axons
 were largely excitatory, where as cells with contralaterally projecting
 axons were inhibitory.
 Together, these observations are beginning to reveal circuit organization
 motifs important for persistent neural activity.
\end_layout

